  "summary": "The circulatory system is an integrated transport network comprising the heart (dual pump), blood vessels (pressure-conducting arteries, resistance-regulating arterioles, exchange-capable capillaries, and capacitance veins), and blood (plasma and cellular components). Cardiac output ($CO = HR \\times SV$) is regulated by preload, afterload, and contractility via the Frank-Starling mechanism and autonomic control. Blood flow distribution follows $Q = \\Delta P/R$, with arteriolar resistance ($R \\propto 1/r^4$) enabling precise regional control. Capillary exchange obeys Fick's law of diffusion and Starling's forces for fluid balance. Oxygen transport depends on hemoglobin's cooperative binding ($Y = \\frac{(P_{O_2})^n}{(P_{50})^n + (P_{O_2})^n}$), while tissue oxygen consumption is quantified by the Fick principle. The system adapts dynamically: at rest, flow prioritizes brain and kidneys; during exercise, skeletal muscle receives up to 85% of output; in shock, compensatory mechanisms preserve vital organ perfusion. Integration with respiratory, renal, and endocrine systems maintains homeostasis of blood gases, fluid volume, electrolytes, and pH. Understanding these principles is essential for managing cardiovascular diseases, optimizing athletic performance, and treating critical illness."
